---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Peptide Bond Chemistry"
  description="Understanding the chemistry of peptide bonds, including formation, structure, and conformational properties."
>
  <nav class="mb-8">
    <a
      href="/learn"
      class="text-sm font-medium text-[#0D9488] hover:underline focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-[#0D9488] focus:ring-offset-2 rounded"
    >
      &larr; Back to Learning Paths
    </a>
  </nav>

  <article class="max-w-3xl">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-extrabold text-slate-900 mb-4">Peptide Bond Chemistry</h1>
    <p class="text-sm font-medium text-slate-400 mb-8">Fundamentals &middot; Intermediate</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-8 mb-4">Introduction</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      The peptide bond is the covalent chemical bond linking two amino acids together. It is the
      fundamental connection that forms the backbone of all peptides and proteins. Understanding
      peptide bond chemistry is essential for grasping protein structure, function, and synthesis.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-8 mb-4">Peptide Bond Formation</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      Peptide bonds form through a <strong>condensation reaction</strong> (also called dehydration
      synthesis). The carboxyl group of one amino acid reacts with the amino group of another,
      releasing a water molecule.
    </p>
    <div class="bg-slate-100 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-sm text-slate-700 mb-6">
      AA1-COOH + H2N-AA2 &rarr; AA1-CO-NH-AA2 + H2O
    </div>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      In biological systems, this reaction is catalyzed by the ribosome during translation. In the
      laboratory, it requires activating reagents to overcome the thermodynamic barrier.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-8 mb-4">Partial Double Bond Character</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      The peptide bond has partial double bond character due to <strong>resonance</strong> between two
      canonical forms. This resonance gives the peptide bond approximately 40% double bond character,
      resulting in:
    </p>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-slate-600 space-y-2 mb-6">
      <li>Restricted rotation around the C-N bond</li>
      <li>Planar geometry</li>
      <li>Higher energy barrier for rotation (approximately 60-90 kJ/mol)</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-8 mb-4">Planar Geometry</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      The peptide bond is planar, meaning the six atoms involved (C&alpha;1, C, O, N, H, C&alpha;2)
      lie in the same plane. This planarity is a direct consequence of the partial double bond
      character and has profound implications for protein folding.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-8 mb-4">Trans vs Cis Configuration</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      Peptide bonds can exist in two configurations:
    </p>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-slate-600 space-y-2 mb-4">
      <li><strong>Trans:</strong> The carbonyl oxygen and amide hydrogen are on opposite sides (more stable)</li>
      <li><strong>Cis:</strong> The carbonyl oxygen and amide hydrogen are on the same side (less stable)</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      The trans configuration is energetically favored due to steric repulsion between side chains.
      Approximately 99.6% of peptide bonds in proteins are trans. The exception is X-Pro bonds, where
      cis configuration occurs more frequently (~6%) due to reduced steric clash.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-8 mb-4">Ramachandran Plot</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      The <strong>Ramachandran plot</strong> (&phi;-&psi; plot) is a fundamental tool for analyzing
      protein backbone conformation. It plots the dihedral angles phi (&phi;) and psi (&psi;) for
      each amino acid residue.
    </p>
    <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
      <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
        <thead>
          <tr class="border-b-2 border-slate-200">
            <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-bold text-slate-900">Secondary Structure</th>
            <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-bold text-slate-900">&phi; (degrees)</th>
            <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-bold text-slate-900">&psi; (degrees)</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="border-b border-slate-100">
            <td class="py-2 px-4 text-slate-700">&alpha;-helix (right-handed)</td>
            <td class="py-2 px-4 text-slate-600">-57</td>
            <td class="py-2 px-4 text-slate-600">-47</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-slate-100">
            <td class="py-2 px-4 text-slate-700">&beta;-sheet (parallel)</td>
            <td class="py-2 px-4 text-slate-600">-119</td>
            <td class="py-2 px-4 text-slate-600">+113</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-slate-100">
            <td class="py-2 px-4 text-slate-700">&beta;-sheet (antiparallel)</td>
            <td class="py-2 px-4 text-slate-600">-139</td>
            <td class="py-2 px-4 text-slate-600">+135</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-slate-100">
            <td class="py-2 px-4 text-slate-700">3<sub>10</sub> helix</td>
            <td class="py-2 px-4 text-slate-600">-49</td>
            <td class="py-2 px-4 text-slate-600">-26</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-8 mb-4">Bond Lengths</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      The resonance structure is evidenced by bond lengths intermediate between single and double
      bonds:
    </p>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-slate-600 space-y-2 mb-4">
      <li><strong>C-N bond:</strong> 1.33 &Aring; (single bond: 1.49 &Aring;, double bond: 1.27 &Aring;)</li>
      <li><strong>C=O bond:</strong> 1.24 &Aring; (typical carbonyl: 1.21 &Aring;)</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-8 mb-4">Hydrogen Bonding</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      The peptide bond serves as both hydrogen bond donor (N-H) and acceptor (C=O). These hydrogen
      bonds are crucial for stabilizing secondary structures (&alpha;-helices, &beta;-sheets),
      maintaining protein tertiary structure, and mediating protein-protein interactions. In
      &alpha;-helices, hydrogen bonds form between residues i and i+4.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-8 mb-4">Peptide Bond Hydrolysis</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
      The peptide bond is thermodynamically unstable but kinetically stable. Hydrolysis is slow
      without catalysis because the resonance-stabilized transition state has high activation energy,
      the leaving group (NH2-) is a strong base, and water is a poor nucleophile. Enzymes (proteases)
      catalyze hydrolysis by activating water molecules, stabilizing the tetrahedral intermediate, and
      providing acid-base catalysis.
    </p>
  </article>

  <nav class="mt-12 pt-8 border-t border-slate-200 flex justify-between items-center">
    <a
      href="/learn/amino-acids"
      class="text-sm font-medium text-[#0D9488] hover:underline focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-[#0D9488] focus:ring-offset-2 rounded"
    >
      &larr; Previous: 20 Standard Amino Acids
    </a>
    <a
      href="/learn/structure"
      class="text-sm font-medium text-[#F97316] hover:underline focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-[#F97316] focus:ring-offset-2 rounded"
    >
      Next: Protein Structure Levels &rarr;
    </a>
  </nav>
</BaseLayout>
